President Muhammadu Buhari has called for the quick passage of the 2021 budget by the National Assembly. Speaking on Thursday while presenting the N13trn budget proposal to the lawmekers, Buhari said passing it on time will ensure early implementation from January 2021. As part of measures to contain the COVID-19 outbreak, the president was accompanied to the National Assembly by only the vice president, Yemi Osinbajo and a handful of ministers. In his presentation, the president said the allocation to education had been increased by 65 percent while the Second Niger Bridge has reached 46 percent completion. Personnel cost, he was remained the single largest item on the expenditure list, expressing determination to totally eliminate ghost workers. Some of the major highlights in the budget include a N128bn allocation made to the National Assembly. The president also directed that there be more vigilant monitoring of revenue generating agencies of government. The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) on Wednesday reported 155 new cases of COVID-19 infections in eight states of the country. The total number of confirmed cases of the coronavirus disease now stands at 59,738, with 7,222 still active. 51,403 patients have been discharged, while the death toll has remained 1,113 for four days running. Lagos State reported the highest number of new cases with 84 infections. The state still has the most confirmed cases, reporting 19,776 of which 4,322 are still active. The Federal Capital Territory (FCT) which reported only seven new cases has 5,765 confirmed cases. 467 are active cases. Plateau reported no new case case but 617 active cases and 3,498 confirmed. The six remaining states that reported new cases include Rivers, which had 31 cases, Kaduna with 12 and Osun with 10 new infections. Oyo State had six new cases, Ogun State had three, while Kwara State reported two new infections of the coronavirus disease.